Opiate deaths data analysis

Death certificate data where death involved opioids between 2006-2015
data: http://mjwebster.github.io/DataJ/spreadsheets/opiate_deaths.csv
record layout: http://mjwebster.github.io/DataJ/spreadsheets/opiatedeaths_recordlayout.pdf
Source: Minnesota Department of Health
this tutorial uses RStudio, in an RNotebook

#Let's try out some of the things the dplyr package lets you do
#we'll start by just pulling a few of the fields from our dataset using SELECT
#first we have to tell it what dataframe to pull from
#then we will use a pipe (%>%) to connect another operation (in this case "select" to tell it what columns)
#note that the field names are case sensitive; in our data they are all capitalized
#these are commands that come from the dplyr package; only works if you have that installed
opiatedata%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHDATE, GENDER, RACE)
#add a filter to get just women who died
#note the double equal sign on the filter 
opiatedata%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHDATE, GENDER, RACE)%>%filter(GENDER=="F")
#add "arrange" to set the order of the records
#default is ascending
#use  arrange(desc(DEATHDATE)) to make it go descending
opiatedata%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHDATE, GENDER, RACE)%>%filter(GENDER=="F")%>%arrange(DEATHDATE)
#filter by more than one column
#this is like using "and" -- need to meet both criteria
opiatedata%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHDATE, GENDER, RACE)%>%filter(GENDER=="F", RACE=="BLACK")%>%arrange(DEATHDATE)
#filter on multiple values from the same column
opiatedata%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHDATE, GENDER, RACE)%>%filter( RACE %in% c("BLACK", "ASIAN"))%>%arrange(DEATHDATE)
#up until now we've just been displaying our results on the fly
#this time let's make a new dataframe from the results of our query
#first you need to assign your dataframe a name and then use "<-" to assign the query to it
#in this case, I want all the fields included, so I'm not going to use select
#but I just want the women, so we'll use filter
#it won't display anything below, but you'll see a new dataframe in the environment box
femaledeaths <- opiatedata%>%filter(GENDER=="F")
#now we can query our new dataframe
#let's just run a simple query to find the youngest female who died
#NOTE: If you want to use a field for arrange, it must also be in select
femaledeaths%>%select(LASTNAME, DEATHCOUNTY, DEATHDATE, RACE, agegroup, AGEYEARS)%>%arrange(AGEYEARS)
#LET'S GO BACK TO OUR ORIGINAL DATAFRAME
#summarize your data using group_by and summarize (also referred to as summarise) in dplyr
opiatedata%>%group_by(GENDER)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#summarize on a different field
opiatedata%>%group_by(agegroup)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#let's use mutate, which is part of dplyr, to add another column to our answer that 
#generates the percentage of total for each group
#notice the math is taking the number from the new numdeaths column and then dividing
#by the total of that same column
#I've added a multiplication by 100 to put it into a whole number to make it easier to read
opiatedata%>%group_by(GENDER)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())%>%mutate(pctdeaths=(numdeaths/sum(numdeaths))*100)
#let's see how many people are of hispanic/latino ethnicity
opiatedata%>%group_by(HISPANICETHNICITY)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#notice in the last query we had inconsistent (or dirty) data
#we can clean that up by creating a new field that we populate with some code
#create new field and set it to the values from the old field
opiatedata$hispanic_new <- opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY
#now we'll change the contents of the hispanic_new field depending what value was in the old field
opiatedata$hispanic_new[opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY == "Hispanic"] <- "HISPANIC"
opiatedata$hispanic_new[opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY == "HISPANIC"] <- "HISPANIC"
opiatedata$hispanic_new[opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY == "Non-Hispanic"] <- "NON-HISPANIC"
opiatedata$hispanic_new[opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY == "NOT HISPANIC"] <- "NON-HISPANIC"
opiatedata$hispanic_new[opiatedata$HISPANICETHNICITY == "UNKNOWN"] <- "UNKNOWN"
#now we'll re-run that query except this time using our new field; and we'll tack on a percentage 
opiatedata%>%group_by(hispanic_new)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())%>%mutate(pct=(numdeaths/sum(numdeaths))*100)
#I'd like to count up the number of deaths each year, but our data doesn't include a separate column
#showing the year. It only has the deathdates. 
#but we can use lubridate, a package that is part of tidyverse to strip out the year portion of the date
opiatedata%>%group_by(year(DEATHDATE))%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#Alternatively we could add that year column as a new column to our existing data frame
#first you assign a name to the new data frame. if we use the old one, it will just write over it
#then you tell it what data frame to use
#then you use mutate -- giving your new field a name (in this case "deathyr")
#then you use the year function from lubridate to pull the year out of the deathdate
#note that I'm specificying which dataframe to get deathdate from by putting "opiatedata$" in front of it
#this won't display anything below, but if you open the table from the environment window you'll see new field
opiatedata <- opiatedata%>%mutate(deathyr = year(opiatedata$DEATHDATE))
#Let's start making some charts using ggplot2, which is also part of tidyverse
#if your chart is going to be based on a summarized version of your data
#then you first need to create a dataframe that you can point to
#we'll make one based on the number of deaths each year
deaths_by_year <- opiatedata%>%group_by(deathyr)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#oftentimes you will need to tell R exactly what order to present the bars in the chart
#you do this by setting the factor levels on the field (in thise case by year)
#note that you have to put the years in the opposite order than you want
deaths_by_year$deathyr <- factor(deaths_by_year$deathyr, levels=c("2015", "2014", "2013", "2012", "2011", "2010", "2009", "2008", "2007", "2006"))
#then we create a dataframe to chart
#I tend to use the same name, but tack on "_chart"" at the end to help understand my workflow
#right after "ggplot" you put in the name of the dataframe where you're getting the data
#the x value is the groups
#the y value is the numeric value that determines the length of the bars
#
deaths_by_year_chart <- ggplot(deaths_by_year, aes(x = deathyr, y = numdeaths)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    coord_flip() +     #this makes it a horizontal bar chart instead of vertical
  labs(title = "Number of opiate deaths by year in MN", 
       subtitle = "2006-2015",
       caption = "Graphic by MaryJo Webster",
       x="Year",
       y="Number of deaths")
#here's where we tell it to plot the chart in the window below
#note you can right-mouse click on the chart and save it to your desktop
plot(deaths_by_year_chart)

#let's add a little to this -- some color and some labels
#in the geom_bar line we'll add color for the outside edges and a fill color for inside (use hex codes)
#in the geom_text line we add the numeric label; nudge moves it so it's not right on the edge
#theme_hc is part of the ggplots themes -- based off High Charts
deaths_by_year_chart_2 <- ggplot(deaths_by_year, aes(x = deathyr, y = numdeaths)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color="black", fill="#59A897") +
    geom_text(stat="identity", nudge_x=0, nudge_y=-10, label=paste0(round(deaths_by_year$numdeaths,0)))+
    coord_flip() +     #this makes it a horizontal bar chart instead of vertical
  theme_hc()+
  labs(title = "Number of opiate deaths by year in MN", 
       subtitle = "2006-2015",
       caption = "Graphic by MaryJo Webster",
       x="Year",
       y="Number of deaths")
#here's where we tell it to plot the chart in the window below
#note you can right-mouse click on the chart and save it to your desktop
plot(deaths_by_year_chart_2)

#now let's make it vertical
#first we need to reset the order; it works differently for vertical charts
deaths_by_year$deathyr <- factor(deaths_by_year$deathyr, levels=c("2006", "2007", "2008", "2009", "2010", "2011", "2012", "2013", "2014", "2015"))
#notice that this time nudge is a positive number, so it goes farther off the bar
#theme_void gets rid of the background grid
#notice we changed the fill color
deaths_by_year_chart_vertical <- ggplot(deaths_by_year, aes(x = deathyr, y = numdeaths)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color="black", fill="#445193") +
  theme_void()+
    geom_text(stat="identity", nudge_x= 0, nudge_y=10, label=paste0(round(deaths_by_year$numdeaths,0)))+
  labs(title = "Number of opiate deaths by year in MN", 
       subtitle = "2006-2015",
       caption = "Graphic by MaryJo Webster",
       x="Year",
       y="Number of deaths")
#here's where we tell it to plot the chart in the window below
#note you can right-mouse click on the chart and save it to your desktop
plot(deaths_by_year_chart_vertical)

#hex color codes:
#http://www.color-hex.com/
#make a line chart instead
death_by_date <- opiatedata%>%group_by(deathyr)%>%summarize(numdeaths=n())
#this sets the x axis labels correctly
death_by_date$deathyr <- factor(death_by_date$deathyr, levels=c("2006", "2007", "2008", "2009", "2010", "2011", "2012", "2013", "2014", "2015"))
#theme_tufte is part of the ggthemes package 
#the group=1 puts the deathyrs into groups and helps plot the line correctly; 
#since deathyr is a factor (not numeric), it needs this to pull everything together correctly
death_by_year_line <- ggplot(data=death_by_date, aes(x = death_by_date$deathyr, y = numdeaths, group=1)) +
                  geom_line(stat="identity", color="red", size=1.5)+  #this draws the line
                            #color and size are optional
                  geom_point(size=2)+  #this adds a point at each stop along the line, size is optional
  theme_tufte()+   #is part of the ggthemes package +
       labs(title="Minnesota opioid deaths by year",
            subtitle = "2006-2015",
       caption = "Graphic by MaryJo Webster",
       x="Year",
       y="Number of deaths")
plot(death_by_year_line)

#notice that our title and labels are all smaller; that's due to theme_tufte styling
#linechart tutorial:
#http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-line-plot-quick-start-guide-r-software-and-data-visualization
#info on themes:
#http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-themes-and-background-colors-the-3-elements
#ON YOUR OWN:  make another chart by agegroup 
#step 1: create a dataframe that summarizes your data by agegroup
#step 2: set the factor order
#step 3: create the plot
#step 4: run/display the plot
#create a scatterplot between death date and person's age; 
#color code based on the age group
#add a trend line (although it's flat)
#need this for Windows machine to correctly find the Arial font family
windowsFonts(Arial=windowsFont("TT Arial")) 
#here's the scatterplot
#notice that we didn't need to make a separate dataframe; we're pulling from the main one
Age_year_scatterplot <- ggplot(opiatedata, aes(x = DEATHDATE, y = AGEYEARS)) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14, base_family = "Arial") + 
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5, aes(color = agegroup)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, color = "black", linetype = "dotdash", size = 0.3) +
  labs(title = "Opioid-related deaths", 
       subtitle = "Source: Minnesota Department of Health",
       caption = "Graphic by MaryJo Webster",
       x="Date of death",
       y="Age")
#change the order of the groups so that they appear correclty in legend
opiatedata$agegroup <- factor(opiatedata$agegroup, 
                              levels=c("under 18", "18-25", "26-35", "36-45", "46-55", "56-64", "64 and higher"))
#plot the scatterplot
